  "prompt": "What three books should an economics undergraduate read?",
  "response": "For an economics undergraduate, there are several foundational books that can provide valuable insights and deepen their understanding of the subject. Here are three highly recommended books:\n\n1. **\"Economics\" by Paul Samuelson and William Nordhaus**: This classic textbook offers a comprehensive introduction to economics, covering both microeconomics and macroeconomics. It is well-regarded for its clear explanations, real-world examples, and authoritative coverage of economic principles.\n\n2. **\"The Wealth of Nations\" by Adam Smith**: Often considered the cornerstone of modern economic thought, this seminal work delves into the nature and causes of economic prosperity. It introduces key concepts such as the division of labor, free markets, and the invisible hand, which remain central to economic theory today.\n\n3. **\"Freakonomics: A Rogue Economist Explores the Hidden Side of Everything\" by Steven D. Levitt and Stephen J. Dubner**: This engaging and accessible book demonstrates how economic principles can be applied to understand a wide array of real-world phenomena. It encourages critical thinking and offers a fresh perspective on how incentives shape human behavior.\n\nThese books provide a strong foundation in economic theory, historical context, and practical application, making them essential reads for any economics undergraduate.",
